  "opinion": "As a 20-year-old electrician living in Los Angeles, I don't spend much time on social media—just a few times a month—so fake content isn't something I encounter daily, but it still worries me when I do. I'm dealing with depression, and seeing false information, especially about things I care about like my Islamic faith or hobbies like football and baking, can really bring me down. It makes me feel like the world is more chaotic and untrustworthy, which doesn't help my mental state. I think managing fake content starts with being cautious and not taking everything at face value. For example, when I see a post about a new baking trend or a football match result, I try to check other sources before believing it, even if it means taking a few extra minutes. My low openness and conscientiousness mean I'm not naturally curious or organized, so I have to push myself to do this, but it's worth it to avoid spreading lies. I also rely on my moderate agreeableness to talk things out with my partner or friends when I'm unsure about something online; we discuss it calmly, which helps me feel less alone and more grounded. Since I'm not very extraverted, I don't post much myself, but when I do, I make sure it's about things I know firsthand, like a recipe I've tried or a book I've read. I believe social media platforms should do more to flag fake content, but as users, we have a role too—by not sharing suspicious posts and reporting them when we can. It's about creating a safer space for everyone, especially for people like me who are already struggling with depression and don't need extra stress from misinformation.",
